04223nam a22005655i 9781478007067DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20192020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780070677 a10.1515/97814780070672doi  a(DE-B1597)553426  a(OCoLC)1130902881  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRA566.5.N6bN494 2020 7aHIS0010502bisacsh04a362.109669/12231 aNewell, Stephanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistories of Dirt :bMedia and Urban Life in Colonial and Postcolonial Lagos /cStephanie Newell. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tAUTHOR'S NOTE -- tPREFACE. The Cultural Politics of Dirt in Africa (Dirtpol) Project -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 European Insanitary Nuisances -- t2 Malaria: Lines in the Dirt -- t3 African Newspapers, the "Great Unofficial Public," and Plague in Colonial Lagos -- t4 Screening Dirt: Public Health Movies in Colonial Nigeria and Rural Spectatorship in the 1930s and 1940s -- t5 Methods, Unsound Methods, No Methods at All? -- t6 Popular Perceptions of "Dirty" in Multicultural Lagos -- t7 Remembering Waste -- t8 City Sexualities: Negotiating Homophobia -- tCONCLUSION. Mediated Publics, Uncontrollable Audiences -- tAPPENDIX. Words, Phrases, and Sayings Relating to Dirt in Lagos -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Histories of Dirt Stephanie Newell traces the ways in which urban spaces and urban dwellers come to be regarded as dirty, as exemplified in colonial and postcolonial Lagos. Newell conceives dirt as an interpretive category that facilitates moral, sanitary, economic, and aesthetic evaluations of other cultures under the rubric of uncleanliness. She examines a number of texts ranging from newspaper articles by elite Lagosians to colonial travel writing, public health films, and urban planning to show how understandings of dirt came to structure colonial governance. Seeing Lagosians as sources of contagion and dirt, British colonizers used racist ideologies and discourses of dirt to justify racial segregation and public health policies. Newell also explores possibilities for non-Eurocentric methods for identifying African urbanites' own values and opinions by foregrounding the voices of contemporary Lagosians through interviews and focus groups in which their responses to public health issues reflect local aesthetic tastes and values. In excavating the shifting role of dirt in structuring social and political life in Lagos, Newell provides new understandings of colonial and postcolonial urban history in West Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aEnvironmental healthzNigeriazLagos. 0aPublic healthzNigeriazLagos. 0aSanitationzNigeriazLagos. 0aUrban healthzNigeriazLagos. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069631840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007067zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007067.jpg  a978-3-11-069631-8  DUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles